Sasaral exhales a stream of flame, this tall Slark ignites a small patch of forest and then circles above, waiting for the right moment. What's odd is that when he slows down, the strange, piercing screams behind him also cease. Sasaral forgets that there's a passenger on his back.
"Come on, Tenuk, you've turned into a Slark before, haven't you?"
"It's one thing to fly on your own, and quite another to be dragged away by a massive pink dragon out of the blue!"
"Are you alright, Kayel?"
Kayel clearly disagreed with Nesia's statement, looking paler than usual, his claws deeply embedded in Sazalin's back, having drawn blood from the Slarks, but Sazalin seemed utterly unbothered by it.
"It's nothing, nothing, I smell something. I'd better take care of it!"
"Must you drag us along as well?" Tenuk slid down from Sazalin's back, his tail slithering across the ground, and asked with a sharp tone. "We left Rethvik behind! We abandoned that powerful and feisty behemoth! How is he supposed to find us?"
"He'll figure it out...," Nesia muttered to herself. "Rethvik may be slow to react, but he's not stupid."
"Will Rethvik be driving?"
"He'll certainly be driving."
"Have you ever seen Rethvik drive a car? He doesn't have a truck like yours, and I've never seen him drive a cute little car like Kayel's either. He started taking the bus to work because you always drive us to work. He only has a bicycle."
A burst of laughter interrupted them. Sazalin suddenly burst into unrestrained laughter, but no one knew what he was laughing at. Sazalin took a while to calm down.
"Sorry, sorry, I just pictured it, you and your big, armored friend riding a kid's bike designed for Tumson children. That's just too ridiculous! I wish I had telepathy so I could have seen the look on your face. That thought is just too amusing! I'll have to remember it."
Kayel also laughed because he could imagine what Sazalin was thinking. "Okay, okay. But what did you smell, and why are you flying so fast?"
Sazalin hummed a tune, took off, and quickly disappeared before reappearing and dropping a corpse in front of Nesia. It was an Orosarak, a rare silver-white dragon-like creature. But its head was missing. "Another one dead. I heard their cries. Smelled their blood. I have to protect them, hunt the killer. This is the will of Isisni. Those creatures are nearby."
The powerful Slark suddenly froze. Nesia and Kayel also froze, their attention drawn to a gaping hole at the edge of the clearing. A massive, pitch-black thing was staring at them, emitting a screeching sound. It suddenly spread out two enormous wings and charged forward, its target fixed firmly on Sazalin, with no regard for the three small creatures standing between it and Sazalin. Kayel and Tenok barely managed to dodge to the side, but Nesia found herself dragged to the ground and nearly flung onto Sazalin.
Sazalin grabbed Nesia with one hand, using his long and agile tail to toss her onto his back, before taking off. A black creature with two pairs of wings shot up quickly in pursuit.
Kayel clicked his tongue, drew his rifle from behind him, then opened his bag and pulled out a belt of cartridges. He hung the belt around his chest, convenient for quick access, but soon realized that Nesia, Sazalin, and the monster were nowhere to be seen.
"Hey, Tenok, can you transform into a flying animal?" Kayel asked.
"Do you want to go after it?"
"Enough already."
"But they're a giant monster, after all!"
"So what? This rifle in my hands packs a punch, and I can fire at any moment. All I need is a glimpse of it, and I'll take it down."
Tenuk hesitated for a moment, then stepped back a pace, giving himself some space. With a low, pained groan, Tenuk's body stretched out, his fur changing to scales, his arms transforming into wings. He quickly became a normal, pale blue Slark, but his eyes remained red.
"Come on up."
Tenuk now looks like a fairly ordinary Slark, with rows of scales forming on his back and a pair of spines growing out, making it easy for Kayel to hold on. It took him a long time to take off, but once airborne, he quickly adjusted his course and made a determined effort to catch up.
However, Tenuk and Kayel soon realized they were not facing just one foe. A second dark creature emerged from beneath them, and Tenuk narrowly dodged the collision.
"Maybe this is the other terrifying monster that Rethvik was worried about?" Kayel furrowed his brow, trying to fire at the second creature, but missed, and quickly reloaded.
Tenuk remained silent, preoccupied with flying towards Nesia and Sazalin, as another creature closed in behind them. Kayel clumsily turned around to face the creature, which was gaining on them. Kayel thought this was a good thing, as it would make it easier for him to aim and shoot. Two bullets pierced the creature's upper wing, and it let out a pained bellow before disappearing into the trees. Kayel wasn't sure if it was still following them, but he thought it was definitely falling behind.
In the front, Sazalin was wildly flailing his body, spewing flames at the black creature, while Nesia desperately clung to Sazalin to avoid falling. Although the creature was undoubtedly wounded, it seemed enraged and unwilling to back down, and the fireballs appeared to inflict minimal damage. Once Sazalin steadied himself, Nesia seized the opportunity to retrieve her trusted shotgun. Although the shotgun wouldn't be effective against this creature, the scattered bullets might at least deter the black beast.
